WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.880
Hello and welcome to my talk, Dissecting the quick fix, analysing tech-solutionist solutions.

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:15.240
Let me start with a definition.

00:00:15.240 --> 00:00:18.120
What is tech-solutionism?

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:23.719
Tech-solutionism is the tendency to use technology to solve a societal, political, organisational,

00:00:23.719 --> 00:00:26.600
environmental, what have you, problem.

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:30.160
A few examples should make this more clear.

00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:33.360
Example number one, riots.

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:34.840
What's the problem?

00:00:34.840 --> 00:00:41.560
Well, suppressed population groups, for example, ethnic minorities, are starting to mobilise.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:42.959
What do we observe?

00:00:42.959 --> 00:00:47.900
This is more likely to happen when it's hot, very hot.

00:00:47.900 --> 00:00:49.400
What is the solution?

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:53.200
Well, just install climatisation throughout.

00:00:53.200 --> 00:00:55.240
And what do we gain?

00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:59.360
We don't have to actually address those groups' demands.

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:01.279
Example two, mass shootings.

00:01:01.279 --> 00:01:02.279
What is the problem?

00:01:02.279 --> 00:01:08.760
Since 2014, on average, there has been more than one mass shooting a day in the US.

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:09.760
What do we observe?

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:14.320
You can't always see if someone is carrying a gun.

00:01:14.320 --> 00:01:15.320
What's the solution?

00:01:15.320 --> 00:01:19.199
Well, just install advanced surveillance technology.

00:01:19.199 --> 00:01:20.199
And what do we gain?

00:01:20.199 --> 00:01:25.199
We don't have to change the laws related to gun ownership.

00:01:25.199 --> 00:01:28.639
Example number three, climate change.

00:01:28.639 --> 00:01:30.680
What is the problem?

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:35.239
Climate change is rendering parts of the earth inhabitable and strongly impacts living conditions

00:01:35.239 --> 00:01:37.080
and others.

00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:39.160
What's our observation?

00:01:39.160 --> 00:01:44.919
Time is passing and we are less and less on track to keep the situation under control.

00:01:44.919 --> 00:01:45.919
What's the solution?

00:01:45.919 --> 00:01:51.160
Well, we just move to Mars or somewhere else in space.

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:52.160
What do we gain?

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:59.720
Well, we survive and get to have fun, if that's the kind of thing we find fun, right?

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:05.559
So yeah, I think by now it should be pretty clear what I'm talking about here.

00:02:05.559 --> 00:02:09.800
On the other hand, you probably also have noticed I got more and more into some kind

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:18.240
of cynical tone, like disgust, cynicism, and pure cynicism and just talking that way doesn't

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:19.720
bring us very far.

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:20.720
Why?

00:02:21.279 --> 00:02:30.039
Well, on the one hand, we won't notice less latent solutions, quote, unquote, when it's

00:02:30.039 --> 00:02:31.039
less clear.

00:02:31.039 --> 00:02:36.399
Like, for example, talking about climate change, what about things like geoengineering?

00:02:36.399 --> 00:02:38.160
Isn't that easy?

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:44.919
And also, we're not never going to reach those people who don't already agree with us anyway,

00:02:44.919 --> 00:02:46.000
right?

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.639
So I don't think this is very useful.

00:02:49.639 --> 00:02:55.039
On the other hand, I think what we should try is to understand what is so seductive

00:02:55.039 --> 00:02:57.279
about this thing.

00:02:57.279 --> 00:03:01.960
Well, like the word already says, it solves something.

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:03.679
Good, right?

00:03:03.679 --> 00:03:06.279
It solves a problem.

00:03:06.279 --> 00:03:11.520
Often it solves a hard problem, a problem that otherwise we wouldn't know how to solve,

00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:13.660
how to address even.

00:03:13.660 --> 00:03:17.240
It solves a problem we would have to make sacrifices for.

00:03:17.240 --> 00:03:19.919
And we don't want that, right?

00:03:19.919 --> 00:03:26.839
And often it just solves a problem we're terribly scared about.

00:03:26.839 --> 00:03:33.639
So what I'm going to try to, in this talk is, or what I think we need is some kind of

00:03:33.639 --> 00:03:41.000
framework to analyze those proposals, and a framework which does not just ask the technical

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:47.679
questions, because this is something we are already doing to some degree.

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:54.399
But I think the technical aspect is not enough, and so I'm going to try to propose a very

00:03:54.399 --> 00:04:02.279
simple framework, a framework of W questions, like what, where, when, why, who, to whom,

00:04:02.279 --> 00:04:03.279
how.

00:04:03.279 --> 00:04:08.440
It's not a W anyway, but to address this in a systematic way.

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:14.960
And there I want to focus on the more neglected aspects.

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:21.040
But as I'm going to focus on two of these aspects, let me say what I mean by the rest

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:23.279
of them.

00:04:23.279 --> 00:04:24.839
First what.

00:04:24.839 --> 00:04:27.040
What does the solution do?

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:31.519
And this should include the complete technical workflow, like from where do we get the data

00:04:31.519 --> 00:04:37.640
from, how do we train our machine learning models, how do we evaluate them.

00:04:37.640 --> 00:04:44.279
And in this area, we already have some things like data set documentation, model documentation,

00:04:44.279 --> 00:04:49.000
which is all great, but which is all the technical side of things.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:54.600
Then, where, when, and to whom will the solution be applied?

00:04:54.600 --> 00:05:01.079
And this should include the complete geographic, social, political, et cetera context.

00:05:01.079 --> 00:05:04.880
Then, how will the solution be applied?

00:05:04.880 --> 00:05:07.679
And here, really, the details matter.

00:05:07.679 --> 00:05:11.679
Next, who is implementing the solution?

00:05:11.679 --> 00:05:15.440
There, as you see, I want to talk about more.

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:19.640
And also, why is the solution being developed?

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:23.440
There also, I would like to go into some detail.

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:30.480
So in other words, in this talk, I want to go into the why and the who, because in my

00:05:30.480 --> 00:05:36.160
view, these are the two aspects which are being neglected most in this area.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:39.320
First, let's start with the why.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:40.480
Why.

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:43.320
So what kind of things you're going to hear?

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:51.399
Well, we care, we want to help, we are here for you.

00:05:51.399 --> 00:05:54.679
What kind of things won't you hear in this area?

00:05:54.679 --> 00:05:57.119
And here I'm kind of splitting it up a bit.

00:05:57.679 --> 00:06:02.559
What kind of reasons might individual people have when they implement something or suggest

00:06:02.559 --> 00:06:05.559
something which they won't say?

00:06:05.559 --> 00:06:13.359
Well, for example, if I build this thing, it's going to look on my resume.

00:06:13.359 --> 00:06:19.959
If I build this thing, it might just get me a job at company XYZ.

00:06:19.959 --> 00:06:27.000
If I build this thing, I might be able to create a startup.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:34.119
If I build this thing, I'm going to learn that crazy new technology, X.

00:06:34.119 --> 00:06:40.119
And also, it's just so cool that this can even be done.

00:06:40.119 --> 00:06:50.079
Next, in a more indirect way, when organizations do something, propose something, what are

00:06:50.079 --> 00:06:53.279
the things they don't say?

00:06:53.359 --> 00:07:00.880
Well, if we build this, we are going to strengthen our existing market monopoly.

00:07:00.880 --> 00:07:04.920
If we build this, we're going to distract from that bad thing that recently ran through

00:07:04.920 --> 00:07:06.480
the news.

00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:13.079
If we build this, we're going to be the good guys.

00:07:13.079 --> 00:07:18.779
And now, in a more indirect way, let's think about side effects.

00:07:18.779 --> 00:07:23.619
If we build this, we are going to be able to extract valuable data for our targeted

00:07:23.619 --> 00:07:25.579
advertising.

00:07:25.579 --> 00:07:32.459
If we build this, we are going to get data to feed back into our neural networks.

00:07:32.459 --> 00:07:38.500
If we build this, we are going to have the foot in the door.

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:47.820
If we build this, public institutions will be stuck with us.

00:07:47.859 --> 00:07:53.660
Now, let's step up one level and think this is about technology.

00:07:53.660 --> 00:07:59.540
And technology is something that shapes us, that forms us, our daily lives.

00:07:59.540 --> 00:08:04.500
If we build this, we define how people live.

00:08:04.500 --> 00:08:08.079
If we build this, we define how people think.

00:08:08.079 --> 00:08:12.739
If we build this, we define what people feel.

00:08:12.739 --> 00:08:19.019
If we build this, we define who people are.

00:08:19.019 --> 00:08:24.859
By now, I think it should be clear what I mean by motivations by this thing, the why

00:08:24.859 --> 00:08:26.459
things are built.

00:08:26.459 --> 00:08:32.539
Now, let's switch to the next thing, the who, who builds something.

00:08:32.539 --> 00:08:37.340
And here, I want to be a bit more clear from the outset who I'm talking about because this

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:39.619
can be a bit ambiguous.

00:08:39.619 --> 00:08:43.419
Who could also mean, like, to whom the solution is being applied?

00:08:43.419 --> 00:08:46.799
I'm not talking about that aspect right now.

00:08:46.799 --> 00:08:54.260
What I mean is, spelling it out, who designs, implements, and hosts the solution, who processes

00:08:54.260 --> 00:09:02.099
its data, who knows how it works, and can fix problems.

00:09:02.099 --> 00:09:06.940
So let's take an example.

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:13.619
As an example, I'm going to talk about education technology, also abbreviated as edtech, which

00:09:13.619 --> 00:09:21.500
has been booming a lot over the last years, especially, of course, due to the pandemic.

00:09:21.500 --> 00:09:27.140
And okay, with edtech, what kind of things are you going to hear?

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:33.700
Well, with adaptive technology XYZ, individual learners' needs are being met.

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:40.179
With adaptive technology XYZ, teachers can focus on doing what they do best.

00:09:40.179 --> 00:09:48.299
With technology XYZ, we make learning more effective and efficient.

00:09:48.299 --> 00:09:54.580
What kind of things won't you hear, how it works?

00:09:54.580 --> 00:10:01.900
With technology XYZ, we are going to extract, store, and process lots of very private and

00:10:01.900 --> 00:10:04.460
personal data.

00:10:04.460 --> 00:10:10.700
With technology XYZ, we are constantly monitoring your behavior.

00:10:10.700 --> 00:10:19.739
With technology XYZ, you learn, we are learning from you.

00:10:19.739 --> 00:10:22.580
Now this is about education technology.

00:10:22.580 --> 00:10:23.979
What's education?

00:10:23.979 --> 00:10:28.219
Education is like forming people, shaping young people.

00:10:29.219 --> 00:10:32.500
Yeah, forming people, let's just say it like this.

00:10:32.500 --> 00:10:39.260
So what this really means is we define how people learn.

00:10:39.260 --> 00:10:42.099
We define what is learned.

00:10:42.099 --> 00:10:45.659
We define what deserves to be learned.

00:10:45.659 --> 00:10:51.219
We define what deserves to be forgotten.

00:10:51.219 --> 00:10:58.140
And stepping up a level, somehow a bit more abstract, what is learned?

00:10:58.140 --> 00:10:59.140
Common knowledge.

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:01.619
This is building a culture.

00:11:01.619 --> 00:11:03.859
This is like who we are.

00:11:03.859 --> 00:11:08.780
So what does this mean?

00:11:08.780 --> 00:11:11.260
We define the past.

00:11:11.260 --> 00:11:13.780
We define the present.

00:11:13.780 --> 00:11:16.580
We define the future.

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:19.940
We define what it means to be human.

00:11:19.940 --> 00:11:21.739
Okay.

00:11:21.739 --> 00:11:30.979
By now, you may be wondering, can you say again how this is about the who?

00:11:30.979 --> 00:11:37.940
Yeah, and so before I was saying what I mean by who is who designs, implements, and hosts

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:46.460
the solution, who processes and stores the data, and who knows how it works.

00:11:47.340 --> 00:11:53.140
This who, or let's say like these who's, we can put them on a dimension.

00:11:53.140 --> 00:12:01.739
And here, I want to ask you to go with me and imagine a dimension, a continuous dimension

00:12:01.739 --> 00:12:08.460
with on the one hand, we have the public, and on the other hand, we have the private.

00:12:08.460 --> 00:12:15.059
On the one hand, for the public institution, I'm asking you to imagine an ideal democracy.

00:12:15.059 --> 00:12:21.500
We all know there is no ideal democracy, but we can all strive for one, at least hope

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:24.780
for one, perhaps.

00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:30.979
So on the one, this ideal democracy, on the other hand, for the private institutions,

00:12:30.979 --> 00:12:31.979
this can be anything.

00:12:31.979 --> 00:12:34.859
It can be a corporation, a foundation, an NGO.

00:12:34.859 --> 00:12:38.979
It doesn't really matter the official status.

00:12:38.979 --> 00:12:43.900
What are defining features of these who's on that dimension?

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:50.619
For the ideal democracy, we have a democratic decision process with participation ranging

00:12:50.619 --> 00:12:51.619
on top.

00:12:51.619 --> 00:12:59.020
For the private end of the dimension, we can only say what's lacking, like this democratic

00:12:59.020 --> 00:13:00.020
decision process.

00:13:00.020 --> 00:13:03.080
Otherwise, it could be anything.

00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:05.260
What are defining values?

00:13:05.260 --> 00:13:12.900
For the public institution, these are things like fairness, justice, human rights, accountability.

00:13:12.900 --> 00:13:18.940
For the private institution, again, it will depend on that institution's agenda.

00:13:18.940 --> 00:13:26.380
So now, if I assume this dimension of who, what kind of difference would that make?

00:13:26.380 --> 00:13:34.820
Well, for one, public institutions don't have to gather data to make money.

00:13:34.820 --> 00:13:40.020
Public institutions don't have to keep their trade secrets.

00:13:40.020 --> 00:13:46.099
Public institutions don't need to worry about market position.

00:13:46.099 --> 00:13:54.059
Next, what difference does this make in political and legal respects?

00:13:54.059 --> 00:13:59.260
Public institutions can be held to ensure transparency.

00:13:59.260 --> 00:14:05.659
Public institutions can be held accountable.

00:14:05.659 --> 00:14:12.140
Public institutions can be obliged to be fair.

00:14:12.140 --> 00:14:20.299
And again, stepping up a bit in abstractness, what difference does it make to human rights

00:14:20.299 --> 00:14:22.700
and values?

00:14:22.700 --> 00:14:30.159
Public institutions can be held to prioritize values over feasibility.

00:14:30.159 --> 00:14:36.719
Public institutions can be obliged to respect human rights.

00:14:36.719 --> 00:14:43.599
Public institutions can be held to promote, not erase, individuality.

00:14:43.599 --> 00:14:49.280
Now, you may be wondering, still, I'm not a CEO.

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:51.239
What can I do?

00:14:52.039 --> 00:14:54.440
Well, I don't really know.

00:14:54.440 --> 00:15:00.679
But I think one thing is perhaps we can make choices.

00:15:00.679 --> 00:15:02.440
This will depend.

00:15:02.440 --> 00:15:09.320
Perhaps we can make choices like who we work for, what we vote for, whether we organize

00:15:09.320 --> 00:15:11.400
politically.

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:18.479
Or one step back, perhaps even, we can question the things we are being told, pretty much

00:15:18.479 --> 00:15:22.799
in the spirit of this talk, asking questions.

00:15:22.799 --> 00:15:31.320
Or even perhaps only we can start with a bit of imagination.

00:15:31.320 --> 00:15:35.159
Maybe data science could be different.

00:15:35.159 --> 00:15:43.239
What if data were used not to perpetuate but change the status quo?

00:15:43.239 --> 00:15:50.719
What if data were used to make social relations more egalitarian, more just?

00:15:50.719 --> 00:15:58.000
What if data were used to subvert privileges, not reinforce them?

00:15:58.000 --> 00:15:59.000
Thank you very much for your attention.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:15:59.000


